    <p>Pick one. That's the 120g to 130g upgrade. If you haven't built the 120g habit yet, start there first — see <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120 grams of protein looks like</a> before trying to jump to 130g.</p>

    <h2>Why the 10g Gap Between 120g and 130g Actually Matters</h2>

    <p>Ten grams doesn't sound like much. But compounded over a week, it's 70g of additional protein. Over a month, it's nearly 300g more protein reaching your muscles than at the 120g baseline.</p>

    <p>At the cellular level, that consistent extra stimulus — combined with resistance training — is the difference between holding muscle and slowly losing it. The research on anabolic resistance after 40 shows that older muscle tissue needs more protein input to produce the same muscle-building response. Every gram above the bare minimum closes that gap a little further.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The 130g sweet spot:</strong> For men in the 165–190 pound range training 3+ times per week, 130g sits right at the 1.5g/kg mark — the point where research consistently shows meaningful muscle preservation outcomes. It's not extreme. It's just enough.</p>
    </div>

